1. Task 1

Same as the previous homework (HW 1), the soccer game information of English Premier League from 2011 to today and odd details for 27 bookmakers are taken as data sets. In this task, it is aimed to understand if over/under 2.5 game results can be estimated from the odds using Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and Multidimentional Scaling (MDS) methods.

1.1. Task 1.a

In this task, 5 different bookmakers (Pinnacle, bet365, bwin, ComeOn, Youwin) are selected. The over/under odds are filtered for total handicap of 2.5. Odds for the other bet types are also considered. The odd files are sorted by date and the final odds for the same matchId and odd type are taken. For each game, feature matrix of the odds for 5 selected bookmakers are created.

Meanwile, from the match data, the information on the game outcomes larger and lower than 2.5 is extracted and numarates so that 0 indicates outcome with lower than 2.5 and 1 as higher than 2.5.

These two information plots are converted into wide table data format and merged as a final data table to perform all PCA and MDS calculations. PCA and MDS with Euclidean and Manhattan distance methods are applied on the data sets for 5 bookmakers. Ther results and the related discussions are given below.

The Figures 1, 5, 9 , 13, and 17 show the variances of principal components in descending order for 5 bookmakers. For example in Pinnacle case (Figure 1), as first principal component explains the all properties in 44%, second principal component explains only 25% of that. Therefore, in such a dimension reduction problems,taking at least two of the principle components will make more sense.

An eigenvalue is a number, telling you how much variance there is in the data in that direction, in the example above the eigenvalue is a number telling us how spread out the data is on the line. The eigenvector with the highest eigenvalue is therefore the principal component. In Figures 2, 6, 10 , 14, and 18, distribution of eigenvectors are shown as red arrows. The eigenvectors with higher magnitutes are more effective on explaining the data. Moreover, the closer eigenvectors in plot, the more similarity in representing the data.

Figures 3, 7, 11 , 15, and 19 shows how over/under 2.5 results can be explained in PCA plot. As can be seen all these plots, there is no certain distinction based on colors. It can be concluded that PCA analysis is not good in estimation on over/under 2.5 match results. No distinct grouping is observed in these plots. If all compounds are used in the biplot, it may be more useful to look at the second and third principle components. This is simply because PCA captures the variation that exists in the compound data and you have chosen all compounds. However, most of them will show no significant change (i.e.Â little variation) and so some other underlying source of variation may be captured in the first dimension. These plots are also useful in identifying the outliers in the dataset.

Figures 4, 8, 12 , 16, and 20 are the 3D representation of the PCA results.

1.2. Task 1.b

The Euclidean distance is the ordinary (straight-line) distance between two points, wheras the Manhattan distance is defined as the sum of the lengths of the projections of the line segment between the points onto the coordinate axes. In Figures 21 - 30, Manhattan and Euclidean distance calculated MDS results are shown. There is no distinct difference between Manhattan and Euclidean distance methods. If data was scattering more, it would have been expected to see more robust results in Manhattan distance. However, our odd data scatters in a narrow range.

1.3. Task 1.c

PCA results are expected to be exactly same with MDS - Euclidean results. For example for bookmaker Bet365, they are found exactly same (Figures 7 and 24). However, for bookmaker Pinnacle these two plots (Figures 3 and 22) are found symmetrical on x=0 axis. This can be explained with the fact that each eigenvector can be defined with its orthogonal vectors. Probably, in two different calculations (PCA vs Euclidean), two orthogonal vectors are considered.

In the below sections, PCA results (PC1 vs PC2) on match outcomes are given in color coded representation as both 2-D and 3-D. Figures 31 - 40 shows the 2D and 3D plots of PCA analysis of odds on match outcomes. Unlike over/under 2.5 PCA, match outcome estimation works well in PCA. 3. Task 3

In this task, certain image operations are performed.

3.1. Read & Display the Image

First, using jpeg package, image is read and displayed via rasterImage function. The image of Mona Lisais chosen and given in Figure 41. The original image is in 512 x 512 pixels size.

Figure 41 - The original image in the size of 512x512.

3.2. Color Channels of the Image

The image stores the color channels of red, green, and blue (RGB type). In this task, three color channels are extracted and given in Figure 42.

Figure 42 - RGB color channels of the original image.

3.2. Creating the Noisy Image & Its Color Channels

In order to create a noisy image, uniformly distributed (in 0-0.1 range) noise is added to the original image. The pixel value higher than 1 are assumed as 1. Noisy image is shown in Figure 43.

Figure 43 - The noisy image in the size of 512x512.

Similar to previous color channel extraction, R, G, and B color channels of the noisy image are obtained as in Figure 44.

Figure 44 - RGB color channels of the noisy image.

3.3. Grayscaling the Noisy Image

Here, the noisy image is converted to grayscale image. In order to perform grayscale transformation, average of the color components is taken and normalized. Grayscale image of the colored noisy image can be seen in Figure 45.

Figure 45 - Grayscale of the noisy image.

3.4. Resizing the Noisy Image

Since, PCA calculations will take too long on 512 x 512 pixels image, the image is resized as 200 x 200 pixels via custom-made resize function. The resized, grayscaled, noisy image is given in Figure 46. As can be see, resolution of the image is quite worsened.

Figure 46 - Grayscaled & noisy image in the size of 200x200.

3.5. PCA Analysis on the Noisy Image

As described in the Homework, for the image on Figure 46, 198*198 patches are created as 3 by 3 patches. Then, PCA analysis on patches is performed.

The given PCA plot in Figure 47 shows how each component in PCA explains the image. As can be seen, the first principle component explain the whole image quite well.

First 3 PCs are given in the Figures 48-50. It can be seen obviously that first PC is quite similar to the image, however second and third PCs are weak in representing the image. This is an expected result regarding the proportion of the variances of PC1, PC2, and PC3 changing as 88.6%, 2.9%, and 2.2%, respectively.

Figure 48 - Reconstructed image from the PCA analysis using the PC 1.

Figure 49 - Reconstructed image from the PCA analysis using the PC 2.

Figure 50 - Reconstructed image from the PCA analysis using the PC 3.

require(data.table)

#read data 
matches = readRDS("C:/Users/09172/Desktop/df9b1196-e3cf-4cc7-9159-f236fe738215_matches.rds")
odd_details = readRDS("C:/Users/09172/Desktop/df9b1196-e3cf-4cc7-9159-f236fe738215_odd_details.rds")

data.table(matches)
data.table(odd_details)

matches=unique(matches)
odd_details =unique(odd_details)

matches[,type:=NULL] #deleted since all are soccer

#filter na scores
matches[is.na(score)]

#omit the rows with score = NA & divide the score into 2
matches_played = na.omit(matches,cols = "score") 
matches_played[,c("score1","score2"):=tstrsplit(score,':')]

#add the scores up
matches_played[,totscore:= (as.numeric(score1)+as.numeric(score2))]
matches_played[,IsOver:=as.numeric(totscore>2)]
match_scores = matches_played[,c("leagueId","home", "away","score","date","score1","score2"):=NULL]

## PINNACLE
data_1 =odd_details[bookmaker=='Pinnacle']
# data_x =odd_details[bookmaker=='Pinnacle'& betType=='dc']

#order data in ascending date
odds_1=data_1[order(matchId,oddtype,bookmaker,date)]
# ou bets are evaluated separately
odds_1=odds_1[betType!='ou']
# only total handicap == 2.5 is taken into account
odds_2.5_1 =data_1[totalhandicap=='2.5']

#final odds were taken into account

odds_final_1=odds_1[,list(final_odd=odd[.N]),
                    by=list(matchId,oddtype,bookmaker)]
wide_odds_final_1=dcast(odds_final_1,
                        matchId~oddtype+bookmaker,
                        value.var='final_odd')

odds_2.5_final_1=odds_2.5_1[,list(final_odd=odd[.N]),
                            by=list(matchId,oddtype,bookmaker)]

wide_odds_2.5_final_1=dcast(odds_2.5_final_1,
                            matchId~oddtype+bookmaker,
                            value.var='final_odd')

merged_1=merge(wide_odds_final_1,wide_odds_2.5_final_1,by='matchId')
merged_1=merged_1[complete.cases(merged_1)]

merged_all_1=merge(merged_1,match_scores,by='matchId')


#PCA ANALYSIS
pca=princomp(merged_all_1[,2:8],cor = TRUE)
plot(pca, main = 'Pinnacle odds - PCA analysis')

str(pca)
summary(pca,loadings=T)

# #first component
# barplot(pca$scores[,1])
# 
# #second component
# barplot(pca$scores[,2])

biplot(pca,main="Pinnacle - PCA - Biplot")
plot(pca$scores[,1],pca$scores[,2],col=merged_all_1$IsOver+1,pch=".",cex=5,main = "Pinnacle - PCA Analysis - Over/Under 2.5")
legend(-7, 8, legend=c("UNDER 2.5", "OVER 2.5"),
       col=c(1, 2), pch=".", cex=0.8, pt.cex=5)

require(rgl)
#plot3d(pca$scores[,1:3], col=merged_all_1$totscore+1)
plot3d(pca$scores[,1:3], col=merged_all_1$IsOver+1)

summary(pca$scores)
cor(pca$scores)

summary(merged_1[,2:8])
cor(merged_1[,2:8])
options(max.print = 100)

# MDS 
#MANHATTAN DISTANCE
distance.matrix_m <- dist(scale((merged_1[,2:8]), center=TRUE, scale=TRUE),
                          method="manhattan")

## do the MDS math (this is basically eigen value decomposition)
mds.stuff_m <- cmdscale(distance.matrix_m, eig=TRUE, x.ret=TRUE)

## calculate the percentage of variation that each MDS axis accounts for...
mds.var.per_m <- round(mds.stuff_m$eig/sum(mds.stuff_m$eig)*100, 1)
mds.var.per_m

## now make a fancy looking plot that shows the MDS axes and the variation:
mds.values_m <- mds.stuff_m$points
plot(mds.values_m[,1],mds.values_m[,2],xlab='', ylab='',col=1, pch='.',cex=5, main = "Pinnacle - MDS plot using Manhattan distance")

# distances_e=dist(merged_1[,2:8], method = "euclidean", diag = TRUE, upper = TRUE)
# distances_e[is.na(distances_e)]=0
# mds_e=cmdscale(distances_e,eig=TRUE)
# plot(mds_e$points[,1],mds_e$points[,2],main='',xlab='', ylab='',col=1)
# 
#  x=sum(mds_e$eig[1])/sum(mds_e$eig)
# 
# euclideanMDS=dist(mds)
# sum((as.matrix(euclideanMDS)-as.matrix(distances))^2)

distance.matrix <- dist(scale((merged_1[,2:8]), center=TRUE, scale=TRUE),
                        method="euclidean")

## do the MDS math (this is basically eigen value decomposition)
mds.stuff <- cmdscale(distance.matrix, eig=TRUE, x.ret=TRUE)

## calculate the percentage of variation that each MDS axis accounts for...
mds.var.per <- round(mds.stuff$eig/sum(mds.stuff$eig)*100, 1)
mds.var.per

## now make a fancy looking plot that shows the MDS axes and the variation:
mds.values <- mds.stuff$points
mds.data <- data.frame(X=mds.values[,1],
                       Y=mds.values[,2])
mds.data

plot(mds.values[,1],mds.values[,2],main='Pinnacle - MDS plot using Euclidean distance',xlab='', ylab='',pch='.', cex=5,col=1)

#include=TRUE writes the code on document
#eval=FALSE doesn't run the code during knitting
require(jpeg)
require(rasterImage)
require(gridExtra)
require(grid)

# source("http://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R")
# biocLite("EBImage")
require(EBImage)

img = readJPEG("C:/Users/09172/Desktop/monalisa.jpg", native = FALSE)
str(img)
dim(img)

# > str(img)
# 'nativeRaster' int [1:512, 1:512] -11306389 -11634840 -10976910 -11042189 -11107469 -10712711 -10975623 -11106439 -11763855 -11961234 ...
# - attr(*, "channels")= int 3

plot(c(0, 550), c(0, 550), type = "n", xlab = "", ylab = "")
rasterImage(img,0,0, 512, 512, interpolate = FALSE)


#CHANNELS OF THE IMAGE
img.R = img
img.G = img
img.B = img

img.R[,,2:3] = 0
img.G[,,1]=0
img.G[,,3]=0
img.B[,,1:2]=0

img1 = rasterGrob(img.R)
img2 = rasterGrob(img.G)
img3 = rasterGrob(img.B)
grid.arrange(img1, img2, img3, nrow=1)

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

#ADDITION OF NOISE

noisy_img=img
for(i in 1:3){noisy_img[,,i]=noisy_img[,,i]+matrix(runif(512*512,0,0.1),nrow=512)}
# gives the error of larger than 1 value
noisy_img[noisy_img>1]=1

plot(c(0, 550), c(0, 550), type = "n", xlab = "", ylab = "")
rasterImage(noisy_img,0,0, 512, 512, interpolate = FALSE)


#CHANNELS OF THE NOISY IMAGE
noisy_img.R = noisy_img
noisy_img.G = noisy_img
noisy_img.B = noisy_img

noisy_img.R[,,2:3] = 0
noisy_img.G[,,1]=0
noisy_img.G[,,3]=0
noisy_img.B[,,1:2]=0

noisy_img1 = rasterGrob(noisy_img.R)
noisy_img2 = rasterGrob(noisy_img.G)
noisy_img3 = rasterGrob(noisy_img.B)
grid.arrange(noisy_img1, noisy_img2, noisy_img3, nrow=1)

# CONVERT THE IMAGE TO GRAYSCALE
gray_img= noisy_img[,,1]+noisy_img[,,2]+noisy_img[,,3]
gray_img = gray_img/max(gray_img)
plot(c(0, 550), c(0, 550), type = "n", xlab = "", ylab = "")
rasterImage(gray_img,0,0, 512, 512, interpolate = FALSE)

# RESIZING THE IMAGE
resize = function(img, new_width, new_height) {
  new_img = apply(img, 2, function(y){return (spline(y, n = new_height)$y)})
  new_img = t(apply(new_img, 1, function(y){return (spline(y, n = new_width)$y)}))
  new_img[new_img < 0] = 0
  new_img = round(new_img)
  return (new_img)
}

small_img = resize(gray_img,200,200)

plot(c(0, 200), c(0, 200), type = "n", xlab = "", ylab = "")
rasterImage(small_img,0,0, 200, 200, interpolate = FALSE)


# CONSTRUCT PATCHES
matrix<-matrix(0,40000,9)

for (i in 2:199) {
  for(j in 2:199) {
    matrix[198*(i-2)+j-1,1]<-small_img[i-1,j-1]
    matrix[198*(i-2)+j-1,2]<-small_img[i-1,j]
    matrix[198*(i-2)+j-1,3]<-small_img[i-1,j+1]
    matrix[198*(i-2)+j-1,4]<-small_img[i,j-1]
    matrix[198*(i-2)+j-1,5]<-small_img[i,j]
    matrix[198*(i-2)+j-1,6]<-small_img[i,j+1]
    matrix[198*(i-2)+j-1,7]<-small_img[i+1,j-1]
    matrix[198*(i-2)+j-1,8]<-small_img[i+1,j]
    matrix[198*(i-2)+j-1,9]<-small_img[i+1,j+1]
  }
}
data=matrix


#PCA
pca = princomp(data, cor=TRUE)
plot(pca)

plot(c(0, 200), c(0, 200), type = "n", xlab = "", ylab = "")
rasterImage(pca$scores[,1],0,0, 198, 198, interpolate = FALSE)


#PC1 Image
PC1 = pca$scores[,1]

PC1_img = matrix(0,198,198)

for(k in 1:198){
  for(l in 1:198){
    PC1_img[k,l]=PC1[198*(k-1)+l]
  }
} 
library(RSNNS)
PC1_img_n<-normalizeData(PC1_img,type="0_1")

plot(c(0, 200), c(0, 200), type = "n", xlab = "", ylab = "")
rasterImage(PC1_img_n,0,0, 198, 198, interpolate = FALSE)
